  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's something I've seen play out in the back rooms of Philadelphia's community colleges, where students from my own background struggle to keep their heads above water. My own education stopped at lower secondary, and I know how hard it is to get past the 'you're not cut out for this' whispers that come with being the first in your family to try something new. Stereotype threat is when people's performance suffers because they fear being judged by a group stereotype—like the idea that girls aren't good at math or that people from certain neighborhoods can't handle engineering. For me, it's personal: I've seen my kids, who are now in high school, get nervous before tests because they think they'll prove their parents wrong by failing. Should we address it? Absolutely. But not with big speeches or programs that don't reach the people who need them most. In my town, it's about simple things: teachers who know the kids' names, mentors who don't assume they can't do it, and a community that says, 'You belong here.' The way to fix it isn't through fancy policies but through real talk and real care. I've been depressed lately, and I've realized that when you feel like you don't belong, it's hard to even try. So, yes—address it. Start with the people who are already struggling, not the ones who think they're fine. It's not about changing the system; it's about changing the way we see each other.",
